  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 28.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Even in the third year of Asa",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [We have here (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:8, 23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") a conspicuous instance of the Hebrew habit of counting parts of years as entire years. It is obvious that if Nadab succeeded to the throne in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "second",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (ver. 25) and died in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the third",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " year of Asa, he cannot have reigned two full years] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "king of Judah did Baasha slay him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [As the assassination took place during the siege, it is extremely probable that Baasha, like Omri, was the captain of the host], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and reigned in his stead.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Probably Nadab had showed himself quite unequal to the task of governing, of which reading the army was in that age a principal function (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 8:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is just possible that in the occupation of Gibbethon by Philistines we have a proof of his feebleness and incapacity. Anyhow, when the strong hand of Jeroboam is removed, the fruits of the rebellion at once begin to appear. The contempt and defiance which Jeroboam had showed towards constituted authority are now manifested towards his successor. Baasha only takes a leaf out of Jeroboam's book (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").] 1 Kings 15:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He walked in the ways of his father (Jeroboam) and in his sin, i.e., in the calf-worship introduced by Jeroboam (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 12:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). When Nadab in the second year of his reign besieged Gibbethon, which the Philistines and occupied, Baasha the son of Ahijah, of the house, I the family or tribe, of Issachar, conspired against him and slew him, and after he became king exterminated the whole house of Jeroboam, without leaving a single soul, whereby the prediction of the prophet Ahijah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 14:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) was fulfilled. Gibbethon, which was allotted to the Danites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), has not yet been discovered. It probably stood close to the Philistian border, and was taken by the Philistines, from whom the Israelites attempted to wrest it by siege under both Nadab and Baasha (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), though apparently without success. לא השׁאיר כּל־נשׁמה as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 11:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see the Comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 20:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
